Beautiful pregnancy progression 

To the first positive line on the pregnancy test.⁣
⁣
To that first appointment, and hearing your perfect heartbeat loud and clear.⁣
⁣
To the first ultrasound, and seeing you wiggle on the screen. ⁣
⁣
To the changes that my body went through, as you grew inside of me. ⁣
⁣
To hearing your first cry, and seeing you take your first breath in this world.⁣
⁣
After 9 months of growing and anxiously waiting for you, I can’t believe that you are finally here my baby! ❤️
.
.
@tori.mccain

node.text:
“The most difficult part of birth is the first year afterwards. It is the year of travail – when the soul of a woman must birth the mother inside her. The emotional labour pains of becoming a mother are far greater than the physical pangs of birth; these are the growing surges of your heart as it pushes out selfishness and fear and makes room for sacrifice and love. It is a private and silent birth of the soul, but it is no less holy than the event of childbirth, perhaps it is even more sacred.” – Joy Kusek.

📷 @kulsveenphotovideo

node.text:
Okay okay, I’m not saying raising kids is EASY by any means... but sometimes maintaining your mental state enough to take care of those little people is where the real struggles lie. 

In order to even give the love and affection they need, we have to first take care of ourselves. And sometimes it’s easier said than done. Having a baby puts your mind and your body through a lot of hormonal changes. Depression, anxiety, body image disorders and mood swings are some of the changes you may go through after having a baby. Not to mention the lack of sleep and the isolation of becoming a mom. 🥱😣Whether this is your fourth baby or your first, the hormonal changes are real and they can destroy you if you’re not careful.

Yesterday I was pouring my daughter a glass of milk to go with her chocolate chip cookie. I set the gallon of milk on the table and she decided to be silly and try to shove her cookie through the opening of the milk gallon and got cookie crumbs in the milk. I was not calm by any means! 🤬 I screamed at her and cursed as I huffed to the kitchen to pour the whole gallon of milk into a large bowl and spoon out each individual cookie crumb. 😤 I didn’t handle the situation well. I could have been more calm. I could’ve told her that’s not some thing that we do. I could have explained to her why that was wrong, but instead I yelled at her for doing some thing that she had no idea was not okay. 

If we don’t take care of our own mental health, we won’t be rational parents. Yelling and screaming will be the go to method of problem-solving instead of rational thinking and calm words. 

“You can’t pour from an empty cup”. We need to make sure that we are taking care of ourselves before we can effectively take care of others. 

So take a few minutes for yourself today. Put your baby in a safe place and go outside. Breathe some fresh air and think positive thoughts. 🧘🏻‍♀️ Or actually take a shower without rushing. Or let your spouse stay home with the kids for an hour and you go on a drive by yourself. Whatever!
You got this mama 💪🏼 motherhood is hard but we’re all in this together. 
What’s something you do to take care of your mental state?
@thatmomabigail
